URL reference: https://thenewstack.io/kubernetes-auditing-and-events-monitoring-cluster-activity/
DateReviewed: 2026-01-04
Description: In an interesting twist of fate, a few days back I saw an article with a similar title, which was just a summary, where NOW we have the actual article for discussion. Interestingly this is an excerpt from a longer book, so it's really turtles all the way down. We start with what is meant by logs in Kubernetes -- there are tracking what containers do, what the K8s cluster does, and what the app does in that cluster -- and we call these "events". K8s lets containers manage apps logs, and they usually coral standard out and error somewhere to local storage at least. There is often a logging driver, which is a way to do something else with the logs, typically ship them off the container somewhere. For container related logs, the suggestion is to use a sidecar on each node to collect such info. They point out that klog exists, and along with logr is more of a whole logging solution. logr acts as a decoupler, and can create klog and other outputs. We now pivot to auditing, which is the process of reviewing and analyzing the logs for information. They pose a question - why did a container get evicted by K8s? Auditing is the answer. To get api activities, there is an API plugin called kubernetes_events which we can set up to grab and produce logs. They talk a bit about Fluent Bit, without explaining what it is; I'm guessing a logging aggretator of some sort. They go through some config file bits and tactical considerations. There is one caution - which is that events are informative, best effort supplmental data - so there are no guarantees in the system. They end with a FAQ and some references; actually a good overall piece.
BottomLine: Article that dives into various Kubernetes log areas
==
